Note:
Runa Standard Library: CSV Writer Module

This module provides production-grade CSV writing capabilities with advanced formatting,
streaming output, custom dialects, data validation, and performance optimization.
Designed for high-throughput data export with memory-efficient streaming for large datasets.

Key Features:
- High-performance CSV writing with streaming support
- Custom dialect configuration and automatic escaping
- Data validation and type conversion before writing
- Memory-efficient streaming for large datasets
- Comprehensive error handling and recovery
- AI/ML-friendly batch processing interfaces
- Cross-platform file handling with encoding support
- Schema-driven output formatting and validation

Architecture:
Built on Runa's natural language primitives with optimized string processing and
buffered I/O for maximum performance. Provides both convenience APIs for simple
use cases and advanced streaming interfaces for high-volume data processing.
:End Note

Import "csv/csv" as csv_core
Import "io/file" as file_io
Import "text/text" as text_utils

Note: CSV Writer Types and Configuration

Type CSVWriterState is Dictionary with:
    rows_written as Integer
    bytes_written as Integer
    current_buffer as String
    buffer_size as Integer
    headers_written as Boolean
    encoding as String
    dialect as csv_core.CSVDialect
    options as csv_core.CSVWriterOptions

Type CSVStreamWriter is Dictionary with:
    file_path as String
    state as CSVWriterState
    is_open as Boolean
    auto_flush as Boolean
    validation_enabled as Boolean

Type CSVWriterResult is:
    | WriterSuccess with data as Any
    | WriterFailure with error as csv_core.CSVError

Note: High-Level CSV Writing API

Process called "write_csv" that takes file_path as String and rows as List[csv_core.CSVRow] returns Boolean:
    Note: Write CSV data to file with default options
    Let default_options be csv_core.create_csv_writer_options
    Return csv_core.write_csv_file with path as file_path and rows as rows and options as default_options

Process called "write_csv_with_options" that takes file_path as String and rows as List[csv_core.CSVRow] and options as csv_core.CSVWriterOptions returns Boolean:
    Note: Write CSV data with custom configuration
    Return csv_core.write_csv_file with path as file_path and rows as rows and options as options

Process called "write_csv_with_headers" that takes file_path as String and headers as List[String] and data as List[List[String]] returns Boolean:
    Note: Write CSV data with explicit headers and row data
    Try:
        Let csv_rows be convert_data_to_csv_rows with headers as headers and data as data
        Let options be csv_core.create_csv_writer_options
        Set options.write_header to true
        
        Return csv_core.write_csv_file with path as file_path and rows as csv_rows and options as options
    
    Catch error:
        Return false

Process called "append_csv_rows" that takes file_path as String and rows as List[csv_core.CSVRow] returns Boolean:
    Note: Append CSV rows to existing file
    Try:
        Let options be csv_core.create_csv_writer_options
        Set options.write_header to false
        
        Let csv_content be csv_core.generate_csv_string with rows as rows and options as options
        Let append_result be file_io.append_to_file with path as file_path and content as csv_content
        
        Match append_result:
            When file_io.WriteSuccess:
                Return true
            When file_io.WriteError:
                Return false
    
    Catch error:
        Return false

Note: Streaming CSV Writer Implementation

Process called "create_stream_writer" that takes file_path as String and options as csv_core.CSVWriterOptions returns CSVWriterResult:
    Note: Create streaming CSV writer for large datasets
    Try:
        Let path_validation be validate_output_path with path as file_path
        If not path_validation["is_valid"] as Boolean:
            Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.FileError with:
                path as file_path
                message as path_validation["error_message"] as String
                operation as "stream_create"
        
        Let initial_state be CSVWriterState with:
            rows_written as 0
            bytes_written as 0
            current_buffer as ""
            buffer_size as 8192
            headers_written as false
            encoding as options.encoding
            dialect as options.dialect
            options as options
        
        Let writer be CSVStreamWriter with:
            file_path as file_path
            state as initial_state
            is_open as true
            auto_flush as true
            validation_enabled as options.ai_mode
        
        Note: Initialize file with headers if requested
        If options.write_header:
            Let header_result be prepare_header_line with writer as writer
            Match header_result:
                When WriterSuccess:
                    Note: Headers will be written with first data row
                    Return WriterSuccess with data as writer
                When WriterFailure with error as header_error:
                    Return WriterFailure with error as header_error
        
        Return WriterSuccess with data as writer
    
    Catch error:
        Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.FileError with:
            path as file_path
            message as "Failed to create stream writer: " plus error as String
            operation as "stream_create"

Process called "write_row_to_stream" that takes writer as CSVStreamWriter and row as csv_core.CSVRow returns CSVWriterResult:
    Note: Write single row to streaming CSV writer
    Try:
        If not writer.is_open:
            Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.FileError with:
                path as writer.file_path
                message as "Writer is closed"
                operation as "stream_write"
        
        Note: Validate row if validation is enabled
        If writer.validation_enabled:
            Let validation_result be validate_row_for_writing with row as row and writer as writer
            Match validation_result:
                When WriterFailure with error as validation_error:
                    Return WriterFailure with error as validation_error
                When WriterSuccess:
                    Note: Continue with writing
                    Pass
        
        Note: Write headers if this is the first row and headers are enabled
        If writer.state.options.write_header and not writer.state.headers_written:
            Let header_line be generate_header_line_from_row with row as row and dialect as writer.state.dialect
            Set writer.state.current_buffer to writer.state.current_buffer plus header_line plus writer.state.dialect.lineterminator
            Set writer.state.headers_written to true
        
        Note: Generate CSV line for the row
        Let row_values be csv_core.get_csv_row_values with row as row
        Let csv_line be csv_core.generate_csv_line with fields as row_values and dialect as writer.state.dialect
        
        Note: Add line to buffer
        Set writer.state.current_buffer to writer.state.current_buffer plus csv_line plus writer.state.dialect.lineterminator
        Set writer.state.rows_written to writer.state.rows_written plus 1
        
        Note: Flush buffer if it exceeds buffer size or auto-flush is enabled
        If text_utils.length with text as writer.state.current_buffer is greater than writer.state.buffer_size or writer.auto_flush:
            Let flush_result be flush_writer_buffer with writer as writer
            Match flush_result:
                When WriterFailure with error as flush_error:
                    Return WriterFailure with error as flush_error
                When WriterSuccess:
                    Pass
        
        Let result_data be Dictionary with:
            "rows_written" as writer.state.rows_written
            "bytes_written" as writer.state.bytes_written
            "buffer_size" as text_utils.length with text as writer.state.current_buffer
        
        Return WriterSuccess with data as result_data
    
    Catch error:
        Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.ParseError with:
            line_number as writer.state.rows_written
            message as "Row writing failed: " plus error as String
            field_index as 0

Process called "write_rows_batch" that takes writer as CSVStreamWriter and rows as List[csv_core.CSVRow] returns CSVWriterResult:
    Note: Write multiple rows efficiently to streaming writer
    Try:
        Let batch_results be empty list
        Let successful_writes be 0
        
        For each row in rows:
            Let write_result be write_row_to_stream with writer as writer and row as row
            Match write_result:
                When WriterSuccess with data as write_data:
                    Set successful_writes to successful_writes plus 1
                    Add write_data to batch_results
                When WriterFailure with error as write_error:
                    Note: Return immediately on first error for consistency
                    Return WriterFailure with error as write_error
        
        Let batch_summary be Dictionary with:
            "batch_size" as length of rows
            "successful_writes" as successful_writes
            "total_rows_written" as writer.state.rows_written
            "total_bytes_written" as writer.state.bytes_written
            "individual_results" as batch_results
        
        Return WriterSuccess with data as batch_summary
    
    Catch error:
        Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.ParseError with:
            line_number as writer.state.rows_written
            message as "Batch writing failed: " plus error as String
            field_index as 0

Process called "flush_writer_buffer" that takes writer as CSVStreamWriter returns CSVWriterResult:
    Note: Flush buffered data to file
    Try:
        If text_utils.is_empty with text as writer.state.current_buffer:
            Return WriterSuccess with data as Dictionary with "bytes_flushed" as 0
        
        Let write_result be file_io.append_to_file with path as writer.file_path and content as writer.state.current_buffer
        Match write_result:
            When file_io.WriteSuccess with bytes_written as bytes:
                Let buffer_size be text_utils.length with text as writer.state.current_buffer
                Set writer.state.bytes_written to writer.state.bytes_written plus bytes
                Set writer.state.current_buffer to ""
                
                Let flush_data be Dictionary with:
                    "bytes_flushed" as bytes
                    "total_bytes_written" as writer.state.bytes_written
                
                Return WriterSuccess with data as flush_data
            
            When file_io.WriteError with error as write_error:
                Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.FileError with:
                    path as writer.file_path
                    message as "Failed to flush buffer: " plus write_error.message
                    operation as "buffer_flush"
    
    Catch error:
        Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.FileError with:
            path as writer.file_path
            message as "Buffer flush error: " plus error as String
            operation as "buffer_flush"

Process called "close_stream_writer" that takes writer as CSVStreamWriter returns CSVWriterResult:
    Note: Close streaming writer and flush any remaining data
    Try:
        If not writer.is_open:
            Return WriterSuccess with data as Dictionary with "already_closed" as true
        
        Note: Flush any remaining buffered data
        Let flush_result be flush_writer_buffer with writer as writer
        Match flush_result:
            When WriterFailure with error as flush_error:
                Return WriterFailure with error as flush_error
            When WriterSuccess:
                Pass
        
        Note: Mark writer as closed
        Set writer.is_open to false
        
        Let close_summary be Dictionary with:
            "total_rows_written" as writer.state.rows_written
            "total_bytes_written" as writer.state.bytes_written
            "file_path" as writer.file_path
        
        Return WriterSuccess with data as close_summary
    
    Catch error:
        Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.FileError with:
            path as writer.file_path
            message as "Writer close error: " plus error as String
            operation as "stream_close"

Note: Data Conversion and Formatting

Process called "convert_data_to_csv_rows" that takes headers as List[String] and data as List[List[String]] returns List[csv_core.CSVRow]:
    Note: Convert structured data arrays to CSV row format
    Try:
        Let csv_rows be empty list
        Let line_number be 1
        
        For each row_data in data:
            Set line_number to line_number plus 1
            Let csv_row be csv_core.create_csv_row with:
                fields as row_data
                headers as headers
                line_num as line_number
            
            Add csv_row to csv_rows
        
        Return csv_rows
    
    Catch error:
        Return empty list

Process called "format_row_for_output" that takes row as csv_core.CSVRow and format_options as Dictionary[String, Any] returns csv_core.CSVRow:
    Note: Format row data according to output specifications
    Try:
        Let formatted_row be row
        Let field_keys be csv_core.get_csv_row_keys with row as row
        
        For each field_key in field_keys:
            If format_options contains key field_key:
                Let format_spec be format_options at key field_key as Dictionary[String, Any]
                Let current_value be row at key field_key
                Let formatted_value be apply_field_formatting with value as current_value and format_spec as format_spec
                Set formatted_row at key field_key to formatted_value
        
        Return formatted_row
    
    Catch error:
        Return row

Process called "apply_field_formatting" that takes value as Any and format_spec as Dictionary[String, Any] returns String:
    Note: Apply specific formatting to field value
    Try:
        Let string_value be convert_value_to_string with value as value
        
        If format_spec contains key "type":
            Let target_type be format_spec at key "type" as String
            Set string_value to format_value_by_type with value as string_value and type_name as target_type and spec as format_spec
        
        If format_spec contains key "max_length":
            Let max_length be format_spec at key "max_length" as Integer
            If text_utils.length with text as string_value is greater than max_length:
                Set string_value to text_utils.substring with text as string_value and start as 0 and length as max_length
        
        If format_spec contains key "padding":
            Let padding_spec be format_spec at key "padding" as Dictionary[String, Any]
            Set string_value to apply_padding with text as string_value and padding_spec as padding_spec
        
        Return string_value
    
    Catch error:
        Return convert_value_to_string with value as value

Process called "format_value_by_type" that takes value as String and type_name as String and spec as Dictionary[String, Any] returns String:
    Note: Format value according to specific type requirements
    Try:
        Match type_name:
            When "integer":
                Let parsed_int be parse_integer_safe with text as value
                Return integer_to_string with number as parsed_int
            
            When "float":
                Let parsed_float be parse_float_safe with text as value
                If spec contains key "decimal_places":
                    Let decimal_places be spec at key "decimal_places" as Integer
                    Return format_float_with_precision with number as parsed_float and precision as decimal_places
                Otherwise:
                    Return float_to_string with number as parsed_float
            
            When "currency":
                Let parsed_float be parse_float_safe with text as value
                Let currency_symbol be spec at key "symbol" if spec contains key "symbol" else "$"
                Return currency_symbol plus format_float_with_precision with number as parsed_float and precision as 2
            
            When "percentage":
                Let parsed_float be parse_float_safe with text as value
                Let percentage_value be parsed_float times 100.0
                Return format_float_with_precision with number as percentage_value and precision as 1 plus "%"
            
            When "date":
                Return format_date_string with date_value as value and spec as spec
            
            Otherwise:
                Return value
    
    Catch error:
        Return value

Note: Data Validation and Schema Enforcement

Process called "validate_rows_before_writing" that takes rows as List[csv_core.CSVRow] and schema as Dictionary[String, String] returns CSVWriterResult:
    Note: Validate all rows against schema before writing
    Try:
        Let validation_errors be empty list
        Let row_index be 0
        
        For each row in rows:
            Set row_index to row_index plus 1
            Let row_validation be validate_single_row_schema with row as row and schema as schema
            
            If not row_validation["is_valid"] as Boolean:
                Let error_info be Dictionary with:
                    "row_index" as row_index
                    "line_number" as row["line_number"] if row contains key "line_number" else row_index
                    "validation_errors" as row_validation["errors"]
                
                Add error_info to validation_errors
        
        If length of validation_errors is greater than 0:
            Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.ValidationError with:
                field_name as "schema_validation"
                message as "Schema validation failed for " plus (length of validation_errors as String) plus " rows"
                value as ""
        
        Let validation_summary be Dictionary with:
            "rows_validated" as length of rows
            "validation_passed" as true
            "schema_fields" as dictionary_keys of schema
        
        Return WriterSuccess with data as validation_summary
    
    Catch error:
        Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.ValidationError with:
            field_name as "validation_process"
            message as "Validation process failed: " plus error as String
            value as ""

Process called "validate_row_for_writing" that takes row as csv_core.CSVRow and writer as CSVStreamWriter returns CSVWriterResult:
    Note: Validate single row for streaming writer
    Try:
        Let field_keys be csv_core.get_csv_row_keys with row as row
        
        Note: Check for empty row
        If length of field_keys is equal to 0:
            Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.ValidationError with:
                field_name as "row_structure"
                message as "Empty row cannot be written"
                value as ""
        
        Note: Validate field consistency if this isn't the first row
        If writer.state.rows_written is greater than 0 and writer.state.options.ai_mode:
            Note: In AI mode, ensure consistent field structure
            Let consistency_check be check_row_field_consistency with row as row and writer as writer
            If not consistency_check["is_consistent"] as Boolean:
                Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.ValidationError with:
                    field_name as consistency_check["problematic_field"] as String
                    message as "Row field structure inconsistency"
                    value as ""
        
        Return WriterSuccess with data as Dictionary with "validation_passed" as true
    
    Catch error:
        Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.ValidationError with:
            field_name as "row_validation"
            message as "Row validation failed: " plus error as String
            value as ""

Note: Advanced Output Features  

Process called "write_csv_with_custom_formatting" that takes file_path as String and rows as List[csv_core.CSVRow] and format_config as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Write CSV with advanced formatting options
    Try:
        Let formatted_rows be empty list
        
        For each row in rows:
            Let formatted_row be format_row_for_output with row as row and format_options as format_config
            Add formatted_row to formatted_rows
        
        Let options be csv_core.create_csv_writer_options
        
        Note: Apply custom dialect if specified
        If format_config contains key "dialect_overrides":
            Let dialect_overrides be format_config at key "dialect_overrides" as Dictionary[String, Any]
            Set options.dialect to apply_dialect_overrides with dialect as options.dialect and overrides as dialect_overrides
        
        Return csv_core.write_csv_file with path as file_path and rows as formatted_rows and options as options
    
    Catch error:
        Return false

Process called "export_csv_with_metadata" that takes file_path as String and rows as List[csv_core.CSVRow] and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Export CSV with embedded metadata header
    Try:
        Let metadata_lines be generate_metadata_header with metadata as metadata
        Let options be csv_core.create_csv_writer_options
        
        Note: Write metadata header first
        Let metadata_content be text_utils.join_lines with lines as metadata_lines
        Let write_metadata_result be file_io.write_to_file with path as file_path and content as metadata_content and mode as file_io.CreateOrTruncate
        
        Match write_metadata_result:
            When file_io.WriteSuccess:
                Note: Append CSV data
                Set options.write_header to true
                Let csv_content be csv_core.generate_csv_string with rows as rows and options as options
                Let append_result be file_io.append_to_file with path as file_path and content as csv_content
                
                Match append_result:
                    When file_io.WriteSuccess:
                        Return true
                    When file_io.WriteError:
                        Return false
            
            When file_io.WriteError:
                Return false
    
    Catch error:
        Return false

Note: Helper Functions

Process called "validate_output_path" that takes path as String returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Validate output file path
    Try:
        Let is_valid be true
        Let error_message be ""
        
        If text_utils.is_empty with text as path:
            Set is_valid to false
            Set error_message to "Output path cannot be empty"
        Otherwise if text_utils.length with text as path is greater than 4096:
            Set is_valid to false
            Set error_message to "Output path too long"
        Otherwise:
            Note: Validate path format and directory structure
            Let path_components be text_utils.split with text as path and delimiter as "/"
            If length of path_components is greater than 1:
                Note: Has directory component - validate directory path structure
                Let directory_path be reconstruct_directory_path with components as path_components
                
                Note: Check for invalid path characters
                If text_utils.contains_any_of with text as directory_path and invalid_chars as list containing "<", ">", "|", ":", "*", "?":
                    Set is_valid to false
                    Set error_message to "Invalid characters in directory path"
                
                Note: Check for relative path traversal attempts
                If text_utils.string_contains with text as path and pattern as ".." or
                   text_utils.string_contains with text as path and pattern as "./":
                    Set is_valid to false
                    Set error_message to "Relative path traversal not allowed"
            
            Note: Validate filename component
            Let filename be get_filename_from_path with path as path
            If text_utils.is_empty with text as filename:
                Set is_valid to false
                Set error_message to "Missing filename"
            Otherwise if text_utils.contains_any_of with text as filename and invalid_chars as list containing "<", ">", "|", ":", "*", "?":
                Set is_valid to false
                Set error_message to "Invalid characters in filename"
        
        Return Dictionary with:
            "is_valid" as is_valid
            "error_message" as error_message
    
    Catch error:
        Return Dictionary with:
            "is_valid" as false
            "error_message" as "Path validation failed"

Process called "prepare_header_line" that takes writer as CSVStreamWriter returns CSVWriterResult:
    Note: Prepare header line for writer based on configuration and expected structure
    Try:
        Note: Validate that writer is configured correctly for header writing
        If not writer.state.options.write_header:
            Return WriterSuccess with data as Dictionary with:
                "header_prepared" as true
                "header_required" as false
        
        Note: Check if we have predefined headers from options
        If length of writer.state.headers is greater than 0:
            Let header_line be csv_core.generate_csv_line with fields as writer.state.headers and dialect as writer.state.dialect
            Set writer.state.current_buffer to writer.state.current_buffer plus header_line plus writer.state.dialect.lineterminator
            Set writer.state.headers_written to true
            
            Return WriterSuccess with data as Dictionary with:
                "header_prepared" as true
                "header_written" as true
                "header_content" as header_line
        
        Note: Headers will be determined from first row written
        Return WriterSuccess with data as Dictionary with:
            "header_prepared" as true
            "header_deferred" as true
    
    Catch error:
        Return WriterFailure with error as csv_core.ParseError with:
            line_number as 0
            message as "Header preparation failed: " plus error as String
            field_index as 0

Process called "generate_header_line_from_row" that takes row as csv_core.CSVRow and dialect as csv_core.CSVDialect returns String:
    Note: Generate header line from row field names
    Try:
        Let field_keys be csv_core.get_csv_row_keys with row as row
        Return csv_core.generate_csv_line with fields as field_keys and dialect as dialect
    
    Catch error:
        Return ""

Process called "validate_single_row_schema" that takes row as csv_core.CSVRow and schema as Dictionary[String, String] returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Validate single row against schema
    Try:
        Let is_valid be true
        Let errors be empty list
        
        For each schema_field in dictionary_keys of schema:
            Let expected_type be schema at key schema_field
            
            If row contains key schema_field:
                Let field_value be row at key schema_field as String
                Let type_valid be csv_core.validate_field_type with value as field_value and expected_type as expected_type
                
                If not type_valid:
                    Set is_valid to false
                    Add "Field " plus schema_field plus " has invalid type" to errors
            Otherwise:
                Set is_valid to false
                Add "Required field " plus schema_field plus " is missing" to errors
        
        Return Dictionary with:
            "is_valid" as is_valid
            "errors" as errors
    
    Catch error:
        Return Dictionary with:
            "is_valid" as false
            "errors" as list containing "Schema validation error"

Process called "check_row_field_consistency" that takes row as csv_core.CSVRow and writer as CSVStreamWriter returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Check if row fields are consistent with previous rows by tracking field structure
    Try:
        Let current_field_keys be csv_core.get_csv_row_keys with row as row
        Let current_field_count be length of current_field_keys
        
        Note: In production, we would maintain field tracking state in writer
        Note: For now, implement basic consistency checking based on field count and names
        
        If writer.state.rows_written is equal to 0:
            Note: First row - establish baseline
            Return Dictionary with:
                "is_consistent" as true
                "problematic_field" as ""
                "field_count" as current_field_count
        
        Note: Check field count consistency (basic structural validation)
        Note: In a full implementation, we would track expected field names and types
        Let expected_field_count be length of writer.state.headers
        
        If current_field_count is not equal to expected_field_count:
            Return Dictionary with:
                "is_consistent" as false
                "problematic_field" as "field_count_mismatch"
                "field_count" as current_field_count
        
        Note: Check field name consistency if headers are available
        If length of writer.state.headers is greater than 0:
            For i from 0 to (minimum_of_two with a as current_field_count and b as length of writer.state.headers minus 1):
                Let current_field_name be current_field_keys at index i
                Let expected_field_name be writer.state.headers at index i
                
                If current_field_name is not equal to expected_field_name:
                    Return Dictionary with:
                        "is_consistent" as false
                        "problematic_field" as current_field_name
                        "field_count" as current_field_count
        
        Return Dictionary with:
            "is_consistent" as true
            "problematic_field" as ""
            "field_count" as current_field_count
    
    Catch error:
        Return Dictionary with:
            "is_consistent" as false
            "problematic_field" as "consistency_check_error"

Process called "minimum_of_two" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return minimum of two integer values
    If a is less than or equal to b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b

Process called "convert_value_to_string" that takes value as Any returns String:
    Note: Convert any value to string representation
    Try:
        If value is equal to None:
            Return ""
        
        Note: Handle different types
        Return value as String
    
    Catch error:
        Return ""

Process called "apply_padding" that takes text as String and padding_spec as Dictionary[String, Any] returns String:
    Note: Apply padding to text based on specification
    Try:
        Let target_length be padding_spec at key "length" as Integer
        Let pad_char be padding_spec at key "character" if padding_spec contains key "character" else " "
        Let align be padding_spec at key "align" if padding_spec contains key "align" else "left"
        
        Let current_length be text_utils.length with text as text
        If current_length is greater than or equal to target_length:
            Return text
        
        Let padding_needed be target_length minus current_length
        Let padding be repeat_string with char as pad_char and count as padding_needed
        
        Match align:
            When "left":
                Return text plus padding
            When "right":
                Return padding plus text
            When "center":
                Let left_pad be padding_needed divided by 2
                Let right_pad be padding_needed minus left_pad
                Let left_padding be repeat_string with char as pad_char and count as left_pad
                Let right_padding be repeat_string with char as pad_char and count as right_pad
                Return left_padding plus text plus right_padding
            Otherwise:
                Return text plus padding
    
    Catch error:
        Return text

Process called "apply_dialect_overrides" that takes dialect as csv_core.CSVDialect and overrides as Dictionary[String, Any] returns csv_core.CSVDialect:
    Note: Apply custom overrides to CSV dialect
    Try:
        Let new_dialect be dialect
        
        If overrides contains key "delimiter":
            Set new_dialect.delimiter to overrides at key "delimiter" as String
        
        If overrides contains key "quotechar":
            Set new_dialect.quotechar to overrides at key "quotechar" as String
        
        If overrides contains key "escapechar":
            Set new_dialect.escapechar to overrides at key "escapechar" as String
        
        If overrides contains key "lineterminator":
            Set new_dialect.lineterminator to overrides at key "lineterminator" as String
        
        Return new_dialect
    
    Catch error:
        Return dialect

Process called "generate_metadata_header" that takes metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns List[String]:
    Note: Generate metadata header lines for CSV file
    Try:
        Let header_lines be empty list
        
        Add "# CSV Export Metadata" to header_lines
        Add "# Generated: " plus get_current_timestamp to header_lines
        
        For each key in dictionary_keys of metadata:
            Let value be metadata at key key
            Let metadata_line be "# " plus key plus ": " plus convert_value_to_string with value as value
            Add metadata_line to header_lines
        
        Add "" to header_lines  Note: Empty line before CSV data
        
        Return header_lines
    
    Catch error:
        Return list containing "# Metadata generation failed"

Note: Numeric Formatting Functions

Process called "parse_integer_safe" that takes text as String returns Integer:
    Note: Safely parse integer with error handling
    Try:
        If csv_core.is_valid_integer with text as text:
            Return parse_integer_from_string with text as text
        Otherwise:
            Return 0
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0

Process called "parse_float_safe" that takes text as String returns Float:
    Note: Safely parse float with error handling
    Try:
        If csv_core.is_valid_float with text as text:
            Return parse_float_from_string with text as text
        Otherwise:
            Return 0.0
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "integer_to_string" that takes number as Integer returns String:
    Note: Convert integer to string representation
    Try:
        If number is equal to 0:
            Return "0"
        
        Let is_negative be number is less than 0
        Let absolute_number be number if not is_negative else 0 minus number
        Let digits be empty list
        
        While absolute_number is greater than 0:
            Let digit be absolute_number modulo 10
            Let digit_char be digit_to_char with digit as digit
            Add digit_char to digits
            Set absolute_number to absolute_number divided by 10
        
        Note: Reverse digits to get correct order
        Let result be ""
        If is_negative:
            Set result to "-"
        
        Let digits_count be length of digits
        For i from (digits_count minus 1) down to 0:
            Set result to result plus (digits at index i)
        
        Return result
    
    Catch error:
        Return "0"

Process called "float_to_string" that takes number as Float returns String:
    Note: Convert float to string representation
    Try:
        Note: Production-grade float to string conversion with proper decimal handling
        Let integer_part be truncate_float_to_integer with number as number
        Let fractional_part be number minus (integer_part as Float)
        
        Let integer_string be integer_to_string with number as integer_part
        
        If fractional_part is equal to 0.0:
            Return integer_string
        
        Let fractional_string be format_fractional_part with fraction as fractional_part
        Return integer_string plus "." plus fractional_string
    
    Catch error:
        Return "0.0"

Process called "format_float_with_precision" that takes number as Float and precision as Integer returns String:
    Note: Format float with specified decimal places
    Try:
        Let multiplier be 1.0
        For i from 1 to precision:
            Set multiplier to multiplier times 10.0
        
        Let scaled_number be number times multiplier
        Let rounded_number be round_float with number as scaled_number
        Let formatted_fractional be rounded_number divided by multiplier
        
        Return float_to_string with number as formatted_fractional
    
    Catch error:
        Return float_to_string with number as number

Process called "format_date_string" that takes date_value as String and spec as Dictionary[String, Any] returns String:
    Note: Format date string according to specification
    Try:
        Let output_format be spec at key "format" if spec contains key "format" else "YYYY-MM-DD"
        
        Note: Basic date formatting - production version would handle various formats
        Return date_value
    
    Catch error:
        Return date_value

Note: Additional Helper Functions

Process called "parse_integer_from_string" that takes text as String returns Integer:
    Note: Production integer parsing (reusing logic from reader)
    Let trimmed be text_utils.trim with text as text
    Let is_negative be false
    Let start_index be 0
    
    Let first_char be text_utils.char_at with text as trimmed and index as 0
    If first_char is equal to "-":
        Set is_negative to true
        Set start_index to 1
    Otherwise if first_char is equal to "+":
        Set start_index to 1
    
    Let result be 0
    Let text_length be text_utils.length with text as trimmed
    
    For i from start_index to (text_length minus 1):
        Let digit_char be text_utils.char_at with text as trimmed and index as i
        Let digit_value be char_to_digit with char as digit_char
        Set result to result times 10 plus digit_value
    
    If is_negative:
        Set result to 0 minus result
    
    Return result

Process called "parse_float_from_string" that takes text as String returns Float:
    Note: Production float parsing with comprehensive decimal and scientific notation support
    Try:
        Let trimmed be text_utils.trim with text as text
        If text_utils.is_empty with text as trimmed:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let is_negative be false
        Let start_index be 0
        Let first_char be text_utils.char_at with text as trimmed and index as 0
        
        If first_char is equal to "-":
            Set is_negative to true
            Set start_index to 1
        Otherwise if first_char is equal to "+":
            Set start_index to 1
        
        If start_index is greater than or equal to text_utils.length with text as trimmed:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let integer_part be 0.0
        Let fractional_part be 0.0
        Let divisor be 1.0
        Let has_decimal be false
        Let text_length be text_utils.length with text as trimmed
        
        Note: Process integer and fractional parts
        For i from start_index to (text_length minus 1):
            Let char be text_utils.char_at with text as trimmed and index as i
            
            If char is equal to ".":
                If has_decimal:
                    Return 0.0  Note: Multiple decimal points
                Set has_decimal to true
                Continue
            
            If char is less than "0" or char is greater than "9":
                Note: Check for scientific notation (e/E)
                If char is equal to "e" or char is equal to "E":
                    Let remaining_text be text_utils.substring with text as trimmed and start as i plus 1
                    Let exponent_value be parse_integer_from_string with text as remaining_text
                    Let base_value be integer_part plus fractional_part
                    Return base_value times power_of_10 with exponent as exponent_value
                
                Return 0.0  Note: Invalid character
            
            Let digit_value be char_to_digit with char as char
            
            If has_decimal:
                Set divisor to divisor times 10.0
                Set fractional_part to fractional_part plus (digit_value as Float divided by divisor)
            Otherwise:
                Set integer_part to integer_part times 10.0 plus digit_value as Float
        
        Let result be integer_part plus fractional_part
        
        If is_negative:
            Set result to 0.0 minus result
        
        Return result
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "digit_to_char" that takes digit as Integer returns String:
    Note: Convert digit to character
    Match digit:
        When 0: Return "0"
        When 1: Return "1"
        When 2: Return "2"
        When 3: Return "3"
        When 4: Return "4"
        When 5: Return "5"
        When 6: Return "6"
        When 7: Return "7"
        When 8: Return "8"
        When 9: Return "9"
        Otherwise: Return "0"

Process called "char_to_digit" that takes char as String returns Integer:
    Note: Convert character to digit
    Match char:
        When "0": Return 0
        When "1": Return 1
        When "2": Return 2
        When "3": Return 3
        When "4": Return 4
        When "5": Return 5
        When "6": Return 6
        When "7": Return 7
        When "8": Return 8
        When "9": Return 9
        Otherwise: Return 0

Process called "repeat_string" that takes char as String and count as Integer returns String:
    Note: Repeat character count times
    Let result be ""
    For i from 1 to count:
        Set result to result plus char
    Return result

Process called "truncate_float_to_integer" that takes number as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Truncate float to integer part with proper handling of positive and negative numbers
    Try:
        If number is greater than or equal to 0.0:
            Note: Positive number - truncate by removing fractional part
            Let integer_part be 0
            Let working_number be number
            
            While working_number is greater than or equal to 1.0:
                Set integer_part to integer_part plus 1
                Set working_number to working_number minus 1.0
            
            Return integer_part
        Otherwise:
            Note: Negative number - truncate towards zero
            Let positive_number be 0.0 minus number
            Let integer_part be 0
            Let working_number be positive_number
            
            While working_number is greater than or equal to 1.0:
                Set integer_part to integer_part plus 1
                Set working_number to working_number minus 1.0
            
            Return 0 minus integer_part
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0

Process called "format_fractional_part" that takes fraction as Float returns String:
    Note: Format fractional part of float with proper decimal digit extraction
    Try:
        If fraction is equal to 0.0:
            Return "0"
        
        Let fractional_digits be empty list
        Let working_fraction be fraction
        Let max_digits be 6  Note: Limit precision to avoid infinite loops
        
        For digit_position from 1 to max_digits:
            Set working_fraction to working_fraction times 10.0
            Let digit_value be truncate_float_to_integer with number as working_fraction
            
            If digit_value is greater than 9:
                Set digit_value to 9
            If digit_value is less than 0:
                Set digit_value to 0
            
            Add digit_to_char with digit as digit_value to fractional_digits
            Set working_fraction to working_fraction minus (digit_value as Float)
            
            If working_fraction is less than 0.0001:  Note: Stop when remaining fraction is negligible
                Break
        
        Note: Convert digits to string
        Let result be ""
        For each digit_char in fractional_digits:
            Set result to result plus digit_char
        
        Note: Remove trailing zeros
        While text_utils.length with text as result is greater than 1 and text_utils.char_at with text as result and index as (text_utils.length with text as result minus 1) is equal to "0":
            Set result to text_utils.substring with text as result and start as 0 and length as (text_utils.length with text as result minus 1)
        
        Return result
    
    Catch error:
        Return "0"

Process called "round_float" that takes number as Float returns Float:
    Note: Round float to nearest integer value using proper rounding rules
    Try:
        Let integer_part be truncate_float_to_integer with number as number
        Let fractional_part be number minus (integer_part as Float)
        
        Note: Handle positive numbers
        If number is greater than or equal to 0.0:
            If fractional_part is greater than or equal to 0.5:
                Return (integer_part plus 1) as Float
            Otherwise:
                Return integer_part as Float
        Otherwise:
            Note: Handle negative numbers  
            Let abs_fractional_part be 0.0 minus fractional_part
            If abs_fractional_part is greater than or equal to 0.5:
                Return (integer_part minus 1) as Float
            Otherwise:
                Return integer_part as Float
    
    Catch error:
        Return number

Process called "get_current_timestamp" returns String:
    Note: Get current timestamp for metadata in ISO 8601 format using system-derived values
    Try:
        Note: Generate timestamp based on CSV metadata creation context
        Let current_year be calculate_current_year_from_context
        Let current_month be calculate_current_month_from_context
        Let current_day be calculate_current_day_from_context
        Let current_hour be calculate_current_hour_from_context
        Let current_minute be calculate_current_minute_from_context
        Let current_second be calculate_current_second_from_context
        
        Note: Format timestamp components with proper zero-padding
        Let year_str be integer_to_string with number as current_year
        Let month_str be pad_number_with_zeros with number as current_month and width as 2
        Let day_str be pad_number_with_zeros with number as current_day and width as 2
        Let hour_str be pad_number_with_zeros with number as current_hour and width as 2
        Let minute_str be pad_number_with_zeros with number as current_minute and width as 2
        Let second_str be pad_number_with_zeros with number as current_second and width as 2
        
        Return year_str plus "-" plus month_str plus "-" plus day_str plus "T" plus hour_str plus ":" plus minute_str plus ":" plus second_str plus "Z"
    
    Catch error:
        Return "1970-01-01T00:00:00Z"

Process called "pad_number_with_zeros" that takes number as Integer and width as Integer returns String:
    Note: Pad number with leading zeros to specified width
    Try:
        Let number_str be integer_to_string with number as number
        Let current_width be text_utils.length with text as number_str
        
        If current_width is greater than or equal to width:
            Return number_str
        
        Let zeros_needed be width minus current_width
        Let zero_padding be repeat_string with char as "0" and count as zeros_needed
        
        Return zero_padding plus number_str
    
    Catch error:
        Return integer_to_string with number as number

Process called "reconstruct_directory_path" that takes components as List[String] returns String:
    Note: Reconstruct directory path from components, excluding the filename
    Try:
        If length of components is less than or equal to 1:
            Return ""
        
        Let directory_parts be empty list
        For i from 0 to (length of components minus 2):  Note: Exclude the last component (filename)
            Add components at index i to directory_parts
        
        Let result be ""
        For each part in directory_parts:
            If not text_utils.is_empty with text as result:
                Set result to result plus "/"
            Set result to result plus part
        
        Return result
    
    Catch error:
        Return ""

Process called "get_filename_from_path" that takes path as String returns String:
    Note: Extract filename from full path
    Try:
        Let path_components be text_utils.split with text as path and delimiter as "/"
        If length of path_components is equal to 0:
            Return ""
        
        Return path_components at index (length of path_components minus 1)
    
    Catch error:
        Return ""

Process called "dictionary_keys" that takes dict as Dictionary[String, Any] returns List[String]:
    Note: Get dictionary keys as list
    Let keys be empty list
    For each key in dict:
        Add key to keys
    Return keys